For the first fraction, the conjugate of $3 - 5i$ is $3 + 5i$. So, we can multiply the numerator and denominator of the first fraction by $3 + 5i$ to get rid of the imaginary part in the denominator:

\begin{align*}
\frac{3 + 5i}{3 - 5i} &= \frac{3 + 5i}{3 - 5i} \cdot \frac{3 + 5i}{3 + 5i} \\
&= \frac{(3 + 5i)(3 + 5i)}{(3 - 5i)(3 + 5i)} \\
&= \frac{9 + 15i + 15i + 25i^2}{9 - 5^2i^2} \\
&= \frac{9 + 30i - 25}{9 - 25i^2} \\
&= \frac{-16 + 30i}{9 + 25} \\
&= \frac{-16 + 30i}{34} \\
&= \frac{-8 + 15i}{17}
\end{align*}

Similarly, for the second fraction, we multiply both the numerator and denominator of the second fraction by its conjugate:

\begin{align*}
\frac{3 - 5i}{3 + 5i} &= \frac{3 - 5i}{3 + 5i} \cdot \frac{3 - 5i}{3 - 5i} \\
&= \frac{(3 - 5i)(3 - 5i)}{(3 + 5i)(3 - 5i)} \\
&= \frac{9 - 15i - 15i + 25i^2}{9 - 5^2i^2} \\
&= \frac{9 - 30i - 25}{9 - 25i^2} \\
&= \frac{-16 - 30i}{9 + 25} \\
&= \frac{-8 - 15i}{17}
\end{align*}

